- 'access_type' refers to the type of access, such as view or download;
- 'measure_id' uniquely identifies each measure;
- 'measure_name' is the name of the measure;
- 'data_point_id' uniquely identifies each data point.

- "measure" refers to a specific metric or data point tracked in the system;
- "access" refers to the event of a user viewing or interacting with the data;
- "prediction" refers to forecasts or models based on the data points.

- "Average confidence score" reflects the reliability of the predictions made by the models;
- "Number of predictions" indicates the total predictions each model has generated;
- "Unique identifiers" are used to uniquely identify each model;
- "Creators of these models" refers to the users who created the models.

- 'region' refers to a specific group name in the `groups` table;
- 'version 1' refers to a specific version name in the `versions` table;
- Standard deviation is a measure of the amount of variation or dispersion of a set of values.

- 'Flowers' represent models in the data analysis context;
- 'Petals' represent data points associated with each model;
- 'Brightest colors' represent the highest average confidence scores of the models;
- 'Diverse landscapes' represent the unique cities and regions where the data points are located.

- The 'LSTM' model is a type of neural network used for sequence prediction tasks;
- The 'group_name' 'region' is the top-level group in the hierarchy;
- The 'effective_date' in the city-region relationship indicates when the relationship became active.

- 'stands tall as the leader' refers to the measure with the highest median value;
- 'top-notch' refers to a quality score greater than 0.8;
- 'vast garden of data' is a metaphor for the database.

- 'LSTM' refers to a type of neural network model commonly used for time-series predictions;
- 'Positive average value' indicates that the data points have a non-zero and non-negative average value;
- 'Updated' refers to data points that have a version description containing the word 'update'.

- 'data points' represent individual pieces of information;
- 'predictions' are forecasts or estimates made based on these data points;
- 'confidence score' is a measure of how reliable or certain a prediction is;
- 'average value' is the mean value of all data points in the 'data_points' table;
- 'average confidence score' is the mean confidence score of predictions for data points with values above the average.

- 'Shining stars' refers to models with above-average confidence scores;
- 'Average confidence score' is calculated by averaging the confidence scores of all predictions for a model;
- 'Overall average confidence score' is the average of the average confidence scores across all models.
